Display dye coverage at the 8 slices¶

This notebook displays the processed images where the blue dye has been identified.

General info on the tracer experiment is in the readme.md file in the home folder. Details about the blue dye image processing are in the README_Dye_Images.txt file.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
import os.path

# a few options
export_to_csv = 0
summary_filename = "summary_profiles.csv"

Re-export the summary profile at each slice, if needed¶

This can be useful if one want to compute different statistics than just the dye coverage fraction at each depth

In [ ]:
# check if data needs to be exported
if export_to_csv == 1:

    # Read and process the slice files
    flist = ['Slice1L_data.txt','Slice1R_data.txt',
            'Slice2L_data.txt','Slice2R_data.txt',
            'Slice3L_data.txt','Slice3R_data.txt',
            'Slice4L_data.txt','Slice4R_data.txt']
    dx = 0.1 #pixel size in cm

    concat_series = []
    # loop through all the slices and compute a profile
    for fname in flist:

        # import, process and append the slice data
        relpath = os.path.join("Individual Slices Data", fname) # build path to a slice
        M = np.loadtxt(relpath, dtype='i', delimiter=',')
        profile = pd.Series(M.sum(axis=1)/M.shape[1], name = fname[0:7])
        concat_series.append(profile)

    # combine all slice data into a dataframe
    df = pd.concat(concat_series,axis=1)
    df["depth"] = np.round(dx*np.arange(1,df.shape[0]+1),1)

    # export to csv file
    df.iloc[:, [8,0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7]].to_csv(summary_filename,index=False)

Display the overall tracer coverage at each depth¶

This is obtained by computing, at each depth, the number of pixels with dye over the total number of pixels

In [ ]:
# display the summary profiles

# load the profiles
df = pd.read_csv(summary_filename)

# add an average between left and right pictures
df["Slice1"] = (df["Slice1L"]+df["Slice1R"])/2
df["Slice2"] = (df["Slice2L"]+df["Slice2R"])/2
df["Slice3"] = (df["Slice3L"]+df["Slice3R"])/2
df["Slice4"] = (df["Slice4L"]+df["Slice4R"])/2

# make the figure
colors = ['tab:blue','tab:orange','tab:green','tab:purple']

fig,ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10, 4))

ax[1].plot(df["Slice1"],-df["depth"],color=colors[0],linewidth=1,label="slice 1")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice1L"],-df["depth"],color=colors[0],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 1L")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice1R"],-df["depth"],color=colors[0],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 1R",linestyle='--')

ax[1].plot(df["Slice2"],-df["depth"],color=colors[1],linewidth=1,label="slice 2")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice2L"],-df["depth"],color=colors[1],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 2L")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice2R"],-df["depth"],color=colors[1],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 2R",linestyle='--')

ax[1].plot(df["Slice3"],-df["depth"],color=colors[2],linewidth=1,label="slice 3")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice3L"],-df["depth"],color=colors[2],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 3L")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice3R"],-df["depth"],color=colors[2],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 3R",linestyle='--')

ax[1].plot(df["Slice4"],-df["depth"],color=colors[3],linewidth=1,label="slice 4")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice4L"],-df["depth"],color=colors[3],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 4L")
ax[0].plot(df["Slice4R"],-df["depth"],color=colors[3],linewidth = 0.5,label="slice 4R",linestyle='--')

ax[0].legend()
ax[0].set_ylabel('Depth [cm]')
ax[0].set_xlabel('Fraction of blue dye coverage [-]')
ax[0].set_xlim([-0.01, 1.01])
ax[0].set_title("Summary profiles at each slice (L and R)")

ax[1].legend()
ax[1].set_ylabel('Depth [cm]')
ax[1].set_xlabel('Fraction of blue dye coverage [-]')
ax[1].set_xlim([-0.01, 1.01])
ax[1].set_title("Summary profiles at each slice (overall)")

plt.show()

What we can observe¶

  • The spatial infiltration patterns are spatially very heterogeneous
  • The summary profiles, being an integration over the spatial heterogeneity, are much more regular and they generally resemble a 'classic' infiltration profile
  • For slice 1, the left and right profiles are almost identical. For slices 2,3,4 the left profiles are similar among each others while the right profiles are different.
  • The summary profiles show that most of the top 5 centimeter layers had 60-90% blue dye coverage. The layers between 5-25 cm depth had variable coverage (and we see clearly that the dye was pushed downwards by the second irrigation event, which occurred between slices 2 and 3). The layers below 25 cm have little to no dye coverage.

Summary figure¶

# make the figure (show 2R)
slice_selection = '2R' #can be anything within1L, 1R, 2L, ... , 4R

# select data
fname = f"Slice{slice_selection}_data.txt"
colname = f"Slice{slice_selection}"
M = np.loadtxt(os.path.join("Individual Slices Data",fname), dtype='i', delimiter=',')

# create a colormap
from matplotlib.colors import LinearSegmentedColormap
colors = [(1,1,1), (0, 0, 1)]  # white to blue
n_bins = 2  # Discretizes the interpolation into bins (we just need 2 here)
cmap0 = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("my_list", colors, N=n_bins)

# make the figure
fig,ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(12, 5),width_ratios=[3, 1])

ax[0].imshow(M, interpolation = 'none',cmap=cmap0)
ax[1].plot(df[colname],df["depth"]*10,color='blue',linewidth = 1.5,linestyle='-')

# set axes 0
ax[0].set_title(f"Slice {slice_selection}: (a) dye presence")   
ax[0].set_ylabel('Depth [mm]')
ax[0].set_xlabel('Width [mm]')

# set axes 1
ax[1].set_title("(b) dye coverage")
ax[1].set_xlabel('Coverage fraction [-]')
ax[1].set_xlim([-0.01, 1.01])
ax[1].invert_yaxis()
ax[1].set_ylim(ax[0].get_ylim())

# adjust positioning and labeling
l0, b0, w0, h0 = ax[0].get_position().bounds
l1, b1, w1, h1 = ax[1].get_position().bounds
ax[1].set_position([l0+w0+0.02, b0, w1, h0])
ax[1].set_yticklabels([])

plt.show()

# save the figure to file
save_fig = False
if save_fig:
    fig.savefig(f"Slice_{slice_selection}.png",bbox_inches='tight', pad_inches=0.1)
